It is a bit weird because if I have a scenery object like dave's legs, dave's arms etc.  Then someone types &quot;eat dave's&quot; it will come up with 
&quot;which dave's did you mean&quot;
1. dave's legs
2. dave's arms
etc

So I will put an object in the room called &quot;dave's&quot;, with no description, to stop the menus in that event.  Because I want it to just be wrong to type in &quot;eat daves&quot; rather than it show the menu.  Plus.. say if theres a hidden object on dave &quot;dave's map&quot; or something, which lets say you learn about later on then take from dave whilst he's asleep by now knowing its there, you can &quot;look at map&quot; &quot;take map&quot; whilst before, you had no idea about it.. but with the &quot;eat dave's&quot; everything &quot;dave's&quot; will just come up so something working like that is easily broken by the player.  They will see &quot;dave's map&quot; and every scenery item listed as &quot;dave's&quot; just by tying in something silly like &quot;eat dave's&quot;
